191
21:21.540 --> 21:29.460
We can see that in each case by computing the Euclidean norm squared of
whatever vector is tensored to the standard basis
vector that we isolated,

192
21:29.460 --> 21:36.150
and in each case we have a one quarter which we get by squaring one half times the absolute value squared of alpha

193
21:36.150 --> 21:44.070
plus the absolute value
squared of beta, which is one, and so we get one quarter in each case.

194
21:44.070 --> 21:52.860
It's quite important in
fact that the probabilities of these different outcomes don't depend in any way on the qubit that
Alice wants to transmit.

195
21:52.860 --> 22:02.250
We couldn't have that an arbitrary state comes in up here and comes out down here and yet a measurement revealed
information about that state.

196
22:02.250 --> 22:11.910
If you wanna gain information about an arbitrary quantum state, you're gonna have to disturb
that state in general.

197
22:11.910 --> 22:17.940
Here's a table that describes not only the probabilities
of the different outcomes, but also the state of
the three Qubits together

198
22:17.940 --> 22:22.260
conditioned on each possible
measurement outcome.

199
22:22.260 --> 22:28.380
We get this by normalizing the vectors tensored to the different
standard basis states, but that's easy in this case,

200
22:28.380 --> 22:34.020
we just eliminate the factor of one half to get a unit vector.

201
22:34.020 --> 22:41.760
So, what we have immediately
after Alice measures is that Alice has two uniform
random bits and that's it.

202
22:41.760 --> 22:50.790
In particular, she no longer
has the original state and she doesn't have any
information about it, she just has random bits.

203
22:50.790 --> 22:57.150
Bob's state now does
depend on alpha and beta as well as on the measurement outcomes.

204
22:57.150 --> 23:03.780
If we imagine momentarily
that Alice hasn't yet sent the measurement outcomes
so that Bob doesn't know what the measurement outcomes are,

205
23:03.780 --> 23:09.270
then he wouldn't be able
to gain any information about alpha and beta
from measuring his qubit.

206
23:09.270 --> 23:16.380
These four possibilities
that we have right here are sufficiently scrambled to ensure that no information
about alpha and beta

207
23:16.380 --> 23:25.920
could ever be gained
through a measurement. That has to be true at an intuitive level because otherwise we'd have
faster than light communication.

208
23:25.920 --> 23:33.750
Alice certainly can't
transmit information to Bob without sending anything at all, but of course Alice does
send the measurement outcomes

209
23:33.750 --> 23:41.010
to Bob, so let's expand the table to see what happens when
Bob performs his operations.

210
23:41.010 --> 23:48.270
In this column right here, we have the different operations that Bob effectively performs for each of the possible
outcomes of the measurements

211
23:48.270 --> 23:56.250
like we observed before,
and if we go one by one and we apply that
operation to Bob's qubit, which is the first one, B,

212
23:56.250 --> 24:05.280
we see that we get the same
outcome in all four cases and that outcome is the original state.

213
24:05.280 --> 24:11.940
So, the original state of the qubit Q has been successfully teleported into B.

214
24:11.940 --> 24:20.220
If Bob wants to rename his qubit and call it Q at this point, he's certainly welcome to do that, but the point is that now
he holds the original state

215
24:20.220 --> 24:25.950
that Alice had and of course by necessity, Alice doesn't have it anymore.

216
24:25.950 --> 24:32.490
Notice also that the e-bit
has effectively been burned up through this process,
teleportation has a cost

217
24:32.490 --> 24:40.800
and the cost is one e-bit and two classical bits of communication, and when the protocol is
over, the e-bit is gone.

218
24:40.800 --> 24:47.610
We've now established that
the teleportation protocol works correctly under the assumption that the top qubit is in a quantum state

219
24:47.610 --> 24:53.280
of the form alpha times cat
zero plus beta times cat one.

220
24:53.280 --> 24:59.760
But what happens if the
top qubit is entangled with some other system such as
one of our additional Qubits

221
24:59.760 --> 25:06.150
as we have here on the screen? We might wish to use teleportation
under such circumstances.

222
25:06.150 --> 25:12.420
Maybe Alice and Bob actually
plan to perform teleportation 100 times so that Alice can transmit

223
25:12.420 --> 25:17.670
some 100 qubit quantum register
to Bob, one qubit at a time.

224
25:17.670 --> 25:25.500
Or maybe these additional
Qubits aren't even in Alice's possession at all
and somebody else has them, maybe Alice doesn't even
know that they exist.

225
25:25.500 --> 25:32.850
The question is, does
teleportation still work even though the qubit being teleported is entangled with another system?

226
25:32.850 --> 25:39.510
Here, the state of the qubit Q together with the additional
system that we're considering is expressed as you can see right up here

227
25:39.510 --> 25:46.950
where gamma zero and
gamma one are unit vectors representing quantum states
of this additional system.

228
25:46.950 --> 25:51.600
We can always write an arbitrary state of the combined system in this way.

229
25:51.600 --> 25:59.760
We don't actually even
need alpha and beta here, but if we include them,
then we can take gamma zero and gamma one to be unit vectors

230
25:59.760 --> 26:04.950
and that'll make the
connection to the simpler case we've already considered more transparent.

231
26:04.950 --> 26:12.750
We can go through a
similar analysis to the one that we already went through, but where we also keep track
of this additional system.

232
26:12.750 --> 26:21.300
It's a little bit messier because we have the additional system, but
the idea is exactly the same, here's a very quick summary.

233
26:21.300 --> 26:27.540
This is the initial state, here's the state after
the controlled NOT gate,

234
26:27.540 --> 26:32.490
and here's the state after
the Hadamard operation.

235
26:32.490 --> 26:39.870
If we expand these things
out, we can express that state as you can see right here,

236
26:39.870 --> 26:46.530
that's the state immediately
before Alice's measurements, and if we go through the
possibilities just like before

237
26:46.530 --> 26:52.710
and we consider what
happens when Bob applies whatever operation he's supposed to apply,

238
26:52.710 --> 26:59.040
then we find that indeed
the correct state comes out and the protocol works as expected.

239
26:59.040 --> 27:06.090
In this table by the way, we're using the letter R to
refer to this additional system, and you can see that we're
using a pretty simple trick,

240
27:06.090 --> 27:12.810
which is to decide that we would rather, at least momentarily, order
the systems as B, R, A, Q

241
27:12.810 --> 27:16.980
because that's more convenient for writing the states right here.

242
27:16.980 --> 27:23.400
According to the diagram, the systems should be
ordered as B, A, Q, R,

243
27:23.400 --> 27:29.730
but as long as we make it clear, we can choose a different
ordering that's more convenient.

244
27:29.730 --> 27:36.030
In a nutshell, everything that's happening in this analysis is the
same as what happened in the simpler analysis,

245
27:36.030 --> 27:43.290
but we happen to have
these additional vectors, gamma zero and gamma one
that basically come along for the ride.

246
27:43.290 --> 27:52.620
We always have gamma zero
when there's a factor of alpha and gamma one when
there's a factor of beta and at the end of the day,
it all works out correctly.

247
27:52.620 --> 27:59.730
This is actually not at all surprising, we have a physical process that acts like the identity
operation on a qubit

248
27:59.730 --> 28:09.240
in an arbitrary quantum state, and there's only one
way that that can happen and that is that the operation
is the identity operation.

249
28:09.240 --> 28:16.440
That's a little bit easier to explain using the general formulation
of quantum information, but the point is that by linearity,

250
28:16.440 --> 28:20.730
we really didn't need to go through this additional analysis.

251
28:20.730 --> 28:28.440
Once we know that
teleportation works correctly for a single qubit in isolation, we can conclude that there's
only one possible thing

252
28:28.440 --> 28:35.970
that can describe what the protocol does, and that is that it implements
the identity operation where a qubit comes in right here

253
28:35.970 --> 28:42.420
and it comes out right here, effectively acting as a perfect
noiseless quantum channel.

254
28:42.420 --> 28:49.740
Just a few quick remarks
about teleportation before moving on to the
second example of the lesson, which is superdense coding.

255
28:49.740 --> 28:57.900
First, I think it's important to clarify that teleportation is not an application of quantum information, it's a protocol

256
28:57.900 --> 29:03.510
and specifically it's a
protocol for performing quantum communication.

257
29:03.510 --> 29:12.660
In order for teleportation
as I've described it to be useful, there has to be some reason for performing quantum communication.

258
29:12.660 --> 29:19.170
Second, it's reasonable to speculate that teleportation could, one
day, become a standard way

259
29:19.170 --> 29:26.730
to communicate quantum information, and specifically a process known as entanglement distillation
might potentially be used

260
29:26.730 --> 29:34.860
as a way to communicate Qubits reliably. If Alice and Bob know they're
going to be communicating quantum information or they
have the need to communicate

261
29:34.860 --> 29:42.600
quantum information, then this process of entanglement distillation
could be used to convert a larger number of noisy e-bits

262
29:42.600 --> 29:50.760
into a smaller number
of high quality e-bits that could then be used for noiseless or near noiseless teleportation.

263
29:50.760 --> 29:58.770
The idea is that the process
of entanglement distillation isn't as delicate in some sense, we could accept losses and
if it doesn't work out,

264
29:58.770 --> 30:07.590
then we could just try it again, whereas the actual Qubits that
we would like to communicate might be considered much more precious.

265
30:07.590 --> 30:14.430
Of course, this is all speculation, but the point is that it isn't difficult to hypothesize situations
in which teleportation

266
30:14.430 --> 30:20.280
could be a very practical
way to communicate Qubits.

267
30:20.280 --> 30:27.870
And the final point
concerning teleportation is that the idea behind teleportation and the way that it works
is quite fundamental

268
30:27.870 --> 30:35.730
in quantum information and computation, teleportation is really a cornerstone of quantum information
theory and variations

269
30:35.730 --> 30:42.780
on the idea also often come
up, it's just one example, there are proposals for
implementing different quantum gates

270
30:42.780 --> 30:49.230
using teleportation, but
where different initial states and measurements are
chosen so that the outcome

271
30:49.230 --> 30:54.300
is to apply a chosen operation
rather than to communicate.

272
30:54.300 --> 30:57.840
The next example is superdense coding.

273
30:57.840 --> 31:06.960
Like quantum teleportation,
superdense coding is a protocol and what it accomplishes is complimentary to teleportation.

274
31:06.960 --> 31:13.520
Whereas teleportation allows
one qubit to be transmitted using an e-bit and two
classical bits of communication,

275
31:13.520 --> 31:21.180
superdense coding allows
two classical bits to be transmitted using
an e-bit and one qubit of quantum communication.

276
31:21.180 --> 31:28.860
So, in short, superdense coding allows for the transmission
of classical information and the reason it's
called superdense coding

277
31:28.860 --> 31:34.860
is that it allows for two
classical bits of communication to be packed into a single qubit,

278
31:34.860 --> 31:38.520
but we have to burn an
e-bit to accomplish this.

279
31:38.520 --> 31:42.450
Here's a more precise
explanation of the setup.

280
31:42.450 --> 31:49.380
Once again, we have Alice and Bob, where Alice is the sender
and Bob is the receiver, and this time Alice has two classical bits

281
31:49.380 --> 31:53.010
that she wants to send to Bob.

282
31:53.010 --> 32:00.960
Alice is able to send Bob a single qubit and Alice and Bob share
an e-bit that they can use to help them to accomplish their task,

283
32:00.960 --> 32:05.340
which is for Bob to receive
the two classical bits.

284
32:05.340 --> 32:11.340
Now, there's a sense in which this task may seem less interesting than the task that
teleportation accomplishes,

285
32:11.340 --> 32:18.450
particularly if we view
that sending Qubits is significantly more
difficult or more challenging than sending classical bits,

286
32:18.450 --> 32:26.430
which is a pretty reasonable point of view but it is definitely interesting that it's possible to do this.

287
32:26.430 --> 32:34.158
One reason why it's interesting
is that it is in fact impossible to accomplish
this task of transmitting two classical bits of information

288
32:34.158 --> 32:39.780
using a single qubit without
making use of the e-bit.

289
32:39.780 --> 32:44.940
We know this because of a famous theorem known as Holevo's theorem.

290
32:44.940 --> 32:52.710
Holevo's theorem is
more general than this, and the precise statement
of Holevo's theorem is a bit technical and it
requires some explanation,

291
32:52.710 --> 33:02.640
but one implication of it
is that you cannot transmit any number of classical
bits of communication using fewer Qubits of
quantum communication alone.

292
33:02.640 --> 33:08.790
If you want to reliably transmit two classical bits of
information using Qubits and you don't have an
e-bit to make use of,

293
33:08.790 --> 33:16.020
you're going to have to send to Qubits, so they might as well store the bits that you wanna transmit.

294
33:16.020 --> 33:23.340
Another reason why superdense
coding is interesting is because of the close
complementary relationship it has to teleportation, and
we'll come back to this

295
33:23.340 --> 33:29.940
a little bit later. Here is a quantum circuit description of the superdense coding protocol.

296
33:29.940 --> 33:36.540
For this one, I won't
list out all the steps, but instead we'll just stick with the circuit diagram description.

297
33:36.540 --> 33:42.390
As you can see, we again
have Alice and Bob, where Alice is on the top
and Bob is on the bottom.

298
33:42.390 --> 33:51.240
Here is the e-bit that's
initially shared between Alice and Bob, which has
somehow been established prior to the protocol being run.

299
33:51.240 --> 33:59.190
Alice has two classical bits, A and B, which you can see up here
and through the protocol that the circuit describes,
these two classical bits

300
33:59.190 --> 34:02.820
will end up in the hands of Bob.

301
34:02.820 --> 34:09.450
There's just one qubit
that crosses the line between Alice and Bob, and of course there aren't
any classical bits being sent,

302
34:09.450 --> 34:15.090
it's the transmission of
the two classical bits that's the point of the protocol.

303
34:15.090 --> 34:23.250
You'll also notice that it has
exactly the same components that are used in teleportation, we have a controlled NOT
gate, a Hadamard gate,

304
34:23.250 --> 34:27.270
and a Z and an X-gate
controlled by classical bits.

305
34:27.270 --> 34:33.210
They're arranged differently however, so let's move on to the
analysis to see how it works.

306
34:33.210 --> 34:42.630
To analyze how superdense coding works, let's start by writing
down the Bell basis, which is very much at the
heart of the analysis.

307
34:42.630 --> 34:50.970
What we're going to do is
to first take a look at the effect that Alice's actions
have on the Phi plus state, and what we'll see is
that Alice transforms this

308
34:50.970 --> 34:57.630
Phi plus state into one
of the four Bell states depending on the bits
that she wants to send.

309
34:57.630 --> 35:02.400
So, let's write down a table so that we can keep
track of what's going on.

310
35:02.400 --> 35:10.650
First, if A and B are both zero, then neither the Z-gate nor
the X-gate gets applied, so Alice's actions don't do anything,

311
35:10.650 --> 35:15.210
which is to say that Phi
plus gets mapped to Phi plus.

312
35:15.210 --> 35:22.440
We can also express that as an equation like you see right here,
nothing happens to Alice's qubit and nothing happens to Bob's qubit

313
35:22.440 --> 35:27.150
and doing nothing is represented
by the identity matrix.

314
35:27.150 --> 35:31.110
Now, what happens if A is equal to zero and B is equal to one?

315
35:31.110 --> 35:37.967
Well, because B is equal to one, we apply the Z-gate and
we don't apply the X-gate because A is equal to zero

316
35:37.967 --> 35:41.730
and we see that the overall effect is that Alice performs a Z-gate.

317
35:41.730 --> 35:48.930
Alice is on the right
because she's on the top, although it wouldn't
actually make any difference in this particular
case, the effect is that

318
35:48.930 --> 35:58.290
the Phi plus date gets
snapped to Phi minus, which you can eyeball
from these expressions if you remember how a Z-gate works works.

319
35:58.290 --> 36:05.629
So, we can add this one to our table, there are two more cases to go through, if A is equal to one
and B is equal to zero,

320
36:05.629 --> 36:13.290
then Alice performs an
X-gate which transforms five Phi into Chi plus, and if A is equal to one
and B is equal to one,

321
36:13.290 --> 36:18.300
then Alice performs Z, then
X and we get Chi minus.

322
36:18.300 --> 36:24.960
So, our table tells us what happens in the four possible cases and that is that Alice effectively chooses which one

323
36:24.960 --> 36:32.700
of the four Bell states she
would like to share with Bob, and she has the freedom to choose by acting on her qubit alone

324
36:32.700 --> 36:36.840
and that's a pretty interesting
aspect of entanglement.

325
36:36.840 --> 36:44.640
Alice then sends her qubit
to Bob, at this point, Bob holds one of the four Bell states and he just needs to
figure out which one it is

326
36:44.640 --> 36:47.910
to recover the bits.

327
36:47.910 --> 36:55.950
And we can check that
indeed a controlled NOT gate followed by a Hadamard gate
as we have in the diagram does the right thing.

328
36:55.950 --> 37:03.780
I won't go through them in detail, but if you choose to do that, you'll find that the effect is
as you see here in the table.

329
37:03.780 --> 37:11.340
One way to check that
is simply to compute. Alternatively, we can recognize that we actually already
went through this in reverse

330
37:11.340 --> 37:18.300
in the previous lesson. In the previous lesson we
had the Hadamard gate first and the controlled NOT gate second

331
37:18.300 --> 37:26.430
and we saw that that circuit
mapped standard basis states to Bell states with a pesky
minus sign in one of the cases.

332
37:26.430 --> 37:35.490
When we reverse the order of the gates and we consider the fact
that both of these two gates are their own inverses,
what we get is the inverse,

333
37:35.490 --> 37:42.720
and so what we have in this
case is the action goes in the opposite direction
and the minus sign can choose whichever
side it wants to be on,

334
37:42.720 --> 37:49.980
but otherwise, it's where it belongs, and at this point it's
immediate that the measurement reveals the correct values,

335
37:49.980 --> 37:57.930
the minus sign here doesn't bother us because one appears with
probability one in this case, and that's all there is to the analysis.

336
37:57.930 --> 38:04.500
In a nutshell, Alice picks a Bell state and Bob figures out which one it is.

337
38:04.500 --> 38:12.150
Just a couple of brief remarks
about superdense coding before we move on; first, we should acknowledge
that superdense coding

338
38:12.150 --> 38:20.130
is probably not likely
to be useful or practical in any sense as a means to
transmit classical information.

339
38:20.130 --> 38:26.850
Classical communication
is very inexpensive and physically sending Qubits is challenging to say the least,

340
38:26.850 --> 38:34.800
and so long as that's the case, we wouldn't expect any
practical advantage at all to come from superdense coding.

341
38:34.800 --> 38:39.780
But just because it isn't
likely to be practical doesn't mean that superdense
coding is not interesting.

342
38:39.780 --> 38:46.650
It's very interesting in fact, for one, the underlying idea is
really quite fundamental,

343
38:46.650 --> 38:52.710
and when I refer to the underlying idea, I mean the idea that if Alice
shares a Bell state with Bob,

344
38:52.710 --> 39:02.100
then she can choose to change that state to any other Bell state that
she chooses all by herself, she doesn't need Bob's
help at all to do that.

345
39:02.100 --> 39:09.060
This is a specific example
that concerns the Bell states, but there's a more general underlying idea that concerns the freedom that one player

346
39:09.060 --> 39:16.110
has to transform an entangled state that's shared with another player, and understanding exactly
what that freedom is

347
39:16.110 --> 39:23.010
is an important step in understanding quantum information and we'll see exactly how to describe that freedom in simple

348
39:23.010 --> 39:27.180
and elegant terms In the
third unit of the series.

349
39:27.180 --> 39:34.500
Superdense coding also
provides a concrete example of what you can do with entanglement, which is to allow two classical
bits to be transmitted

350
39:34.500 --> 39:45.636
by sending a single qubit. As I already mentioned, this
is provably not possible by Holevo's theorem without entanglement.

351
39:45.636 --> 39:52.620
We can also consider teleportation and superdense coding together, and we see that they
establish an equivalence

352
39:52.620 --> 39:58.890
between one qubit of quantum communication and two bits of classical communication.

353
39:58.890 --> 40:04.530
As long as you're willing
to spend one e-bit, you can effectively
convert one to the other.

354
40:04.530 --> 40:11.970
Teleportation allows for the
communication of one qubit using two classical bits of communication and superdense coding goes the other way

355
40:11.970 --> 40:18.150
and allows two classical
bits of communication using one qubit of quantum communication.

356
40:18.150 --> 40:26.640
Without spending the e-bit, however, you cannot transform
either one into the other, it's entanglement that
makes this possible.

357
40:26.640 --> 40:35.190
The third and final example
that we'll cover in this lesson is not a protocol but a
game known as the CHSH game.

358
40:35.190 --> 40:41.220
When we talk about a game in this context, we're not talking about something that's meant to be
played for fun or sport,

359
40:41.220 --> 40:47.460
but rather a mathematical abstraction in the sense of game theory for instance.

360
40:47.460 --> 40:55.470
Mathematical abstractions of games are very commonly studied in
economics and computer science, for instance, and there's
quite a lot of value

361
40:55.470 --> 41:01.470
to be found in the abstraction, so games are not all fun
in games as it turns out,

362
41:01.470 --> 41:04.961
although it is fun to think about them.

363
41:04.961 --> 41:13.770
In this particular case, what we have is essentially
a thought experiment that can be described in a
pretty intuitive way as a game.

364
41:13.770 --> 41:23.370
The letters CHSH refer to the authors, John Clauser, Michael
Horne, Abner Shimony, and Richard Holt of a 1969
paper where the example

365
41:23.370 --> 41:30.330
was first described. They didn't describe
it as a game, in fact, and it's pretty common
to refer to this example

366
41:30.330 --> 41:36.060
not as the CHSH game, but
rather as the CHSH inequality.

367
41:36.060 --> 41:41.730
For a computer scientist like me, however, it's just very natural
to describe it as a game.

368
41:41.730 --> 41:48.840
I've already suggested that
mathematical abstractions of games are both important and useful and there are many different
categories of games

369
41:48.840 --> 41:57.000
that can be considered. The CHSH game is an
example of a class of games called non-local games.

370
41:57.000 --> 42:01.440
Here's the setup in general
for a non-local game.

371
42:01.440 --> 42:08.190
We have two players, Alice and Bob, who cooperate as a team, so they either win together
or they lose together.

372
42:08.190 --> 42:14.430
This means that they have no
incentive to act selfishly, so it's essentially the opposite
extreme to zero sum games,

373
42:14.430 --> 42:20.850
which are purely competitive, here the game is purely cooperative.

374
42:20.850 --> 42:24.240
There's a third entity called the referee.

375
42:24.240 --> 42:31.140
The referee isn't a player in the game, but rather the referee
runs the game, and in fact, you can think about the specification

376
42:31.140 --> 42:39.450
of a particular instance
of a non-local game and the specification of a
referee as being equivalent.

377
42:39.450 --> 42:48.420
There's a critically important constraint that's placed on Alice and Bob, which is that once the game starts, they're forbidden from
communicating with one another.

378
42:48.420 --> 42:58.260
They can agree beforehand on
whatever strategy they choose, but no communication
is allowed between them during the game itself.

379
42:58.260 --> 43:06.630
If you like, you can imagine
the game taking place in a secure facility of some sort as if the referee is playing
the role of a detective

380
43:06.630 --> 43:13.080
and Alice and Bob are suspects located in different
rooms in a police station, but another way of
thinking about the setup

381
43:13.080 --> 43:20.550
is that Alice and Bob are
separated by a vast distance and communication is prohibited because the speed of light
doesn't allow for communication

382
43:20.550 --> 43:29.760
to happen quickly enough. If Alice tries to send a
message to Bob for instance, the game will be over by
the time Bob receives it.

383
43:29.760 --> 43:35.940
The way a non-local game
works is that first, the referee asks both
Alice and Bob a question.

384
43:35.940 --> 43:40.950
Alice's question is labeled X and Bob's question is labeled Y.

385
43:40.950 --> 43:49.860
In general, you can think about X and Y as being classical states
from whatever classical states that you like and in the
specific case of the CHSH game,

386
43:49.860 --> 43:53.610
X and Y are bits.

387
43:53.610 --> 43:59.820
Alice and Bob must then provide answers, Alice's answer is labeled A,
and Bob's answer is labeled B,

388
43:59.820 --> 44:08.580
and again, these answers can be viewed as classical states in general and like the questions, they
will be bits in the CHSH game.

389
44:08.580 --> 44:15.389
At this point, the
referee makes a decision, Alice and Bob either win or they lose depending on whether or not
the pair of answers A, B

390
44:15.389 --> 44:23.700
is deemed correct for the
pair of questions X, Y that the referee asked, and I'll say a little bit more
about this in just a moment.

391
44:23.700 --> 44:32.044
First, let's take a
closer look at the referee to understand what it is
that's potentially challenging for Alice and Bob in a non-local game.

392
44:32.044 --> 44:39.330
And what makes a non-local
game potentially challenging is that the referee can use randomness to choose the questions X and Y.

393
44:39.330 --> 44:46.350
That means that Alice
and Bob have uncertainty, they don't know ahead of time what question they're going to be asked, and perhaps more importantly,

394
44:46.350 --> 44:55.560
they don't know what question
the other one received and it's that uncertainty
together with the fact that they can't communicate
that presents the challenge.

395
44:55.560 --> 45:02.760
So, it's similar to the situation where a detective
interrogates two suspects in different rooms, if
the suspects don't know

396
45:02.760 --> 45:09.930
what questions the other one is asked, it's much harder if they're guilty to keep their story straight.

397
45:09.930 --> 45:16.860
Now, I mentioned a short
time ago that the referee makes a determination
that Alice and and Bob have either answered
correctly or incorrectly

398
45:16.860 --> 45:20.610
depending upon the questions
that they were asked.

399
45:20.610 --> 45:28.230
It's assumed that this
determination is made according to some fixed
rule and you can consider any rule that you want,
but whatever it is,

400
45:28.230 --> 45:34.980
it is assumed that Alice
and Bob know the rule, so at least they have a fighting
chance to answer correctly.

401
45:34.980 --> 45:43.530
We'll take a look at the
rule for the CHSH game in a moment, but we could
consider a different rule and we would have a different
example of a non-local game.

402
45:43.530 --> 45:51.240
Some non-local games are interesting and in fact some are quite fascinating in mysterious to this day and
some aren't so interesting,

403
45:51.240 --> 45:54.240
that's just the nature of
the non-local game model.

404
45:54.240 --> 46:01.220
Anyway, these are the two different things that are needed to describe a referee; how exactly are the questions chosen

405
46:01.220 --> 46:06.450
and which answer pairs are correct for each possible question pair.

406
46:06.450 --> 46:12.630
If we have a description
of those two things, then we have a description for the referee and that effectively describes

407
46:12.630 --> 46:16.680
an instance of a non-local game.

408
46:16.680 --> 46:21.330
Now let's take a look at
the CHSH game specifically.

409
46:21.330 --> 46:27.750
The way that the game is
defined or, equivalently, how the referee is defined is as follows;

410
46:27.750 --> 46:36.300
first, as I've already mentioned, the questions and answers are all bits, so the referee sends a bit X
to Alice and a bit Y to Bob,

411
46:36.300 --> 46:43.770
and they each respond with a bit. Alice responds with A
and Bob responds with B.

412
46:43.770 --> 46:50.220
The way the referee chooses
which questions to ask is simple, he chooses
them uniformly at random,

413
46:50.220 --> 47:00.690
so, the pair of questions X, Y is equally likely to be anyone
of the four possibilities, zero, zero, zero, one,
one, zero, and one, one.

414
47:00.690 --> 47:09.180
Finally, the rule that
determines which answers win and which answers lose is
that a pair of answers A, B is correct for the pair of questions X, Y

415
47:09.180 --> 47:16.620
if and only if the exclusive or of A and B is equal to the logical and of X and Y.

416
47:16.620 --> 47:23.430
That may be a little bit easier to digest if we express those conditions
in the form of a table as you see right here.

417
47:23.430 --> 47:29.790
In the first column, we have the four possible question pairs, and in the second column we
have the conditions on A and B

418
47:29.790 --> 47:33.420
that are required for
Alice and Bob to win.

419
47:33.420 --> 47:39.570
In the first three cases,
the and of A and Y is zero, so the exclusive or must be equal to zero

420
47:39.570 --> 47:46.890
in order for them to win,
and that's the same thing as saying that A and B must be equal because A and B are bits,
and the fourth case,

421
47:46.890 --> 47:53.460
the and of X and Y is equal
to one and so the exclusive or of A and B must be equal to one in order for Alice and Bob to win

422
47:53.460 --> 47:57.600
and that's the same thing
as saying that A and B must be different.

423
47:57.600 --> 48:07.740
So, that's the CHSH game, and now we can think about
different possible strategies for Alice and Bob and how
well they can do in this game.

424
48:07.740 --> 48:16.260
Let's start by thinking about
deterministic strategies where Alice's answer A is a
function of the question X that she receives, and
likewise, Bob's answer B

425
48:16.260 --> 48:20.220
is a function of the
question Y that he receives.

426
48:20.220 --> 48:26.790
And as it turns out, no
deterministic strategy can possibly win every time.

427
48:26.790 --> 48:33.390
One way to reason that is
simply to go one by one through all of the possible
deterministic strategies and to check that every one of them loses

428
48:33.390 --> 48:37.770
for at least one of the four
possible question pairs.

429
48:37.770 --> 48:46.560
Alice and Bob, each have
four possible functions to choose from, we saw those
four functions in lesson one, so there are 16 possibilities
to check overall.

430
48:46.560 --> 48:53.550
Another way to see that is to
think about the equations here on the screen, we're thinking
about deterministic strategies

431
48:53.550 --> 48:57.120
where A and B are functions
of X and Y respectively.

432
48:57.120 --> 49:05.010
So for example, A of zero
represents Alice's answer when her question X is equal to zero and a of one represents Alice's answer

433
49:05.010 --> 49:09.180
when her question X is equal to one.

434
49:09.180 --> 49:15.450
These are the four equations
that have to be true in order for the winning
conditions to be met in each of the four cases.

435
49:15.450 --> 49:22.350
For example, if X is equal to
zero and Y is equal to zero, then the exclusive or of A
and B must be equal to zero,

436
49:22.350 --> 49:30.090
whereas in the case that X is equal to one and Y is equal to one, the
exclusive or of A and B must be equal to one.

437
49:30.090 --> 49:40.680
One way we can see that
there's no way to choose the functions A and B so that
these equations are all true, is simply to take the exclusive
or of all of the equations.

438
49:40.680 --> 49:47.962
The exclusive or of any
binary value with itself is equal to zero, and so it follows that the exclusive or
of the left-hand sides

439
49:47.962 --> 49:54.720
is equal to zero, that's
because we have two instances of a zero, two instances of a one,

440
49:54.720 --> 49:59.010
two instances of B zero
and two instances of B one.

441
49:59.010 --> 50:07.110
So, xing them all together
gives us the final answer of zero, but if we take the exclusive or of the right hand sides of the equations,

442
50:07.110 --> 50:13.980
we get one not zero. So the four equations
can't possibly all be true, at least one of them has to be wrong

443
50:13.980 --> 50:21.060
and that will lead to a
loss for Alice and Bob in at least one of the four cases.

444
50:21.060 --> 50:28.980
And so it follows because the referee chooses the questions
uniformly that the probability for Alice and Bob to win
using a deterministic strategy

445
50:28.980 --> 50:33.660
is at most three quarters or 75%.

446
50:33.660 --> 50:41.490
The fact that Alice and and Bob can win with probability three quarters is quite easy to see
actually, if Alice and and Bob both answer zero all
the time, for instance,

447
50:41.490 --> 50:46.710
they'll be correct three
out of the four times.

448
50:46.710 --> 50:53.850
So Alice and Bob can't do
any better than winning 75% of the time using a
deterministic strategy.

449
50:53.850 --> 50:57.911
But what about a probabilistic strategy?

450
50:57.911 --> 51:04.950
Well, it turns out that using
a probabilistic strategy can't help them at all, that's because every
probabilistic strategy

451
51:04.950 --> 51:12.000
can alternatively be viewed
as a random selection of a deterministic strategy just like probabilistic
operations can be viewed

452
51:12.000 --> 51:17.760
as random selections of
deterministic operations, as we saw in the first lesson.

453
51:17.760 --> 51:24.840
The average is never
larger than the maximum, so it follows that a
probabilistic strategy doesn't offer any advantage
in terms of winning

454
51:24.840 --> 51:31.860
over a deterministic strategy. This even includes the possibility that Alice and Bob's random
choices are correlated.

455
51:31.860 --> 51:39.420
So, the bottom line is that winning with probability three quarters is the best that Alice
and Bob can possibly do using any classical strategy,

456
51:39.420 --> 51:42.810
whether it's deterministic
or probabilistic.

457
51:42.810 --> 51:49.584
The natural question to ask at this point is whether Alice and Bob can do any better using a quantum strategy,
and in particular

458
51:49.584 --> 51:57.720
if they share an entangled quantum state which they could have repaired
prior to playing the game, can that help them?

459
51:57.720 --> 52:04.800
The answer is yes, it can, and that is the point of the example and that's why it's so interesting.

460
52:04.800 --> 52:12.810
So let's see exactly how
Alice and Bob can do better in this game using entanglement.

461
52:12.810 --> 52:21.090
The first thing we need to do is to define a quantum state vector Chi
theta for each angle theta, as you can see here on the screen.

462
52:21.090 --> 52:27.480
So, Chi theta is equal to
cosine theta times cat zero plus sine theta times cat
one, and here by the way,

463
52:27.480 --> 52:31.860
we're thinking about
angles in terms of radians.

464
52:31.860 --> 52:38.880
So for example, here's the vector we get when theta is equal to pi over
four, which is 45 degrees.

465
52:38.880 --> 52:48.570
Cosine of pi over four
and sine of pi over four are both equal to one over
the square root of two, so this is just another
name for the plus state.

466
52:48.570 --> 52:55.200
Here's another example when theta is equal to three times pi over eight, and in case you don't
happen to know the sine

467
52:55.200 --> 53:01.620
and cosine of three times pi over eight off the top of your head,
here's a table of the sines and the cosines that we're
actually going to need

468
53:01.620 --> 53:07.530
throughout this example
and includes the ones that we need for this particular vector.

469
53:07.530 --> 53:16.620
Now, if we wanna take the inner product between any two of these vectors
for angles, alpha and beta let's say, it's
straightforward to do that.

470
53:16.620 --> 53:23.910
We only have real number
entries in these vectors so there are no complex
conjugates to worry about and we obtain the product of the cosines

471
53:23.910 --> 53:30.540
plus the product of the the sines, and we can use one of the
so-called angle addition formulas

472
53:30.540 --> 53:36.810
to simplify that, it's the
cosign of the difference between the angles and
because the cosine function

473
53:36.810 --> 53:42.060
is symmetric around zero,
it doesn't actually matter which order we take them in.

474
53:42.060 --> 53:48.420
If you don't have these sorts
of trigonometric identities committed to memory, by
the way, you're not alone, but you don't have to remember them,

475
53:48.420 --> 53:54.480
you can just look them up. This one does make sense
though when you think about the geometric interpretation
of the inner product

476
53:54.480 --> 54:01.260
between real unit vectors as the cosine of the angle between them.

477
54:01.260 --> 54:08.430
If we compute the inner
product of the tensor product of any two of these vectors
with the Phi plus state, we get a similar looking expression

478
54:08.430 --> 54:12.360
except that there's a squared
of two in the denominator.

479
54:12.360 --> 54:18.720
This is the first time
that the Phi plus state has appeared in the context
of this example by the way, and we'll see exactly why we're interested

480
54:18.720 --> 54:25.170
in this particular inner product shortly, but for the moment let's
just observe that we obtain the same expression that we had

481
54:25.170 --> 54:35.730
for the inner product divided
by the square root of two and so we can simplify as before.

482
54:35.730 --> 54:44.010
Next, we'll define a
unitary matrix, U theta, for each angle theta
like you see right here,

483
54:44.010 --> 54:47.910
it's not difficult to
check that this is indeed a unitary matrix.

484
54:47.910 --> 54:56.040
The key thing we need to
recognize is that the vectors si theta is orthogonal to
the vector si theta plus pi over two, and that makes sense

485
54:56.040 --> 55:02.084
because if we rotate by pi over two, which is 90 degrees, we
get an orthogonal vector.

486
55:02.084 --> 55:08.190
If we then multiply U
theta to U theta dagger, we get the identity matrix.

487
55:08.190 --> 55:18.720
Intuitively speaking,
what this matrix does as an operation is to
map si theta to cat zero and si theta plus pi two to cat one.

488
55:18.720 --> 55:24.360
At this point, we have
everything that we need to describe Alice and Bob's strategy.

489
55:24.360 --> 55:31.170
First, just like we had for teleportation and superdense coding, Alice and Bob will start out by sharing an e-bit.

490
55:31.170 --> 55:38.640
Alice holds a qubit A,
bob holds a qubit B, and together the two Qubits
are in the Phi plus state.

491
55:38.640 --> 55:45.300
Alice's actions are as follows; she looks at the bit X that
she receives from the referee,

492
55:45.300 --> 55:54.180
and if X is equal to zero,
she performs U zero on A, which happens to be the
same thing as doing nothing because U zero is the identity matrix,

493
55:54.180 --> 55:59.700
effects is equal to one on the other hand, she applies U pi over four to A.

494
55:59.700 --> 56:08.910
After she applies one
of the two operations, she measures A using a
standard basis measurement and sends whatever result
she gets to the referee.

495
56:08.910 --> 56:15.090
Bob does something very similar, his qubit is called B of course, and he receives Y from the
referee as opposed to X

496
56:15.090 --> 56:20.580
but the key difference is
that he uses different angles for his unitary operations.

497
56:20.580 --> 56:28.500
If Y is equal to zero, he
applies U pi over eight, and if Y is equaled one, he applies u negative pi over eight.

498
56:28.500 --> 56:36.030
And we'll see why these choices of angles are good choices shortly,
it's not at all obvious.

499
56:36.030 --> 56:40.830
And here is a circuit diagram
that expresses this strategy.

500
56:40.830 --> 56:46.860
Bob is in the top and Alice
is on the bottom this time, here is the e-bit that is coming in

501
56:46.860 --> 56:53.910
and these are the unitary
gates that Alice and Bob might or might not apply
depending upon what X and Y are.

502
56:53.910 --> 57:00.330
For this one and this one, we have gates that are being controlled either by the bit X or by the bit Y

503
57:00.330 --> 57:07.680
and for these two right here, we have what kind of
look like control gates except that the circle isn't filled in.

504
57:07.680 --> 57:15.870
And what this means is
that if the control bit is set to zero, then the gate is performed and if the control is set to
one, then nothing happens.

505
57:15.870 --> 57:23.790
So, it's just like an
ordinary control gate except that the roles of zero and one for the control are swapped.

506
57:23.790 --> 57:29.970
So, effectively, Bob
performs this gate right here if Y is equal to zero, he
performs this gate right here

507
57:29.970 --> 57:39.000
if Y is equal to one, and similarly, Alice performs this gate right
here if X is equal to zero, and this gate right here,
if X is equal to one.

508
57:39.000 --> 57:45.750
So, that is Alice and Bob's strategy and now we just need to
figure out how well it works.

509
57:45.750 --> 57:53.100
For the analysis of the quantum strategy that I just described, we
really only need two things at this point, first, the
unitary matrix U Theta

510
57:53.100 --> 57:57.840
is as you see right here, and
second we had this formula.

511
57:57.840 --> 58:05.730
We don't actually even need the definition of the vector si theta anymore, these two equations are all we need.

512
58:05.730 --> 58:12.570
There are four cases to
consider starting with case one, which is that X equal
zero and Y equals zero.

513
58:12.570 --> 58:22.830
And if we look back at the strategy, we'll find that in this
case Alice performs U zero on her qubit and Bob performs
U pi over eight on his qubit.

514
58:22.830 --> 58:29.550
Remember, Alice is on the
bottom and Bob is on the top, so the state that they
obtain looks like this.

515
58:29.550 --> 58:36.930
And by expanding that out
according to the definition of U theta, we get this
expression you see right here.

516
58:36.930 --> 58:42.630
We don't need to expand
that out any further because we have the other
formula to help us out.

517
58:42.630 --> 58:49.950
And if we apply that formula
for each of the four terms, what we get is this.

518
58:49.950 --> 58:58.380
At this point Alice and Bob both measure and here's a table that
explains the distribution of the outcomes.

519
58:58.380 --> 59:05.220
We take the absolute value
squared of the coefficients to get the probabilities, which happens to be the
squares of the coefficients

520
59:05.220 --> 59:09.930
because the coefficients are
all real numbers in this case.

521
59:09.930 --> 59:18.240
If we make use of the
sine and cosine values from earlier in the lesson
along with some symmetries, we can express these probabilities
as we have right here

522
59:18.240 --> 59:21.930
in the last column.

523
59:21.930 --> 59:29.839
Now, what we really care
about is the probability that they win, and remember that, in the case that X and Y are both zero,

524
59:29.839 --> 59:35.370
they win if A and B are equal and they lose if A and B are not equal.

525
59:35.370 --> 59:42.631
If we calculate those probabilities, we find that the probability
that A and B are equal is the sum of this number and this number,

526
59:42.631 --> 59:50.190
which is equal to two plus
root two all over four, which is about 85%.

527
59:50.190 --> 59:56.550
The probability that A and B are not equal is two minus root two all over four, which is naturally one minus the quantity

528
59:56.550 --> 60:04.620
that we just calculated, so
they win with probability about 85% in this case.

529
60:04.620 --> 60:11.070
There are three more cases to consider, but they're all very similar to this one,

530
60:11.070 --> 60:18.300
in the case that X equals
zero and Y equals one, Bob applies U negative pi over eight rather than U pi over eight,

531
60:18.300 --> 60:26.520
the values in the
formulas change somewhat, but we end up with exactly
the same probabilities that we had in the previous case.

532
60:26.520 --> 60:34.890
When X equals zero and Y equals one, Alice and Bob still win
when A and B are equal and so we have exactly the
same winning probability

533
60:34.890 --> 60:38.040
as before.

534
60:38.040 --> 60:45.450
In the third case, when X is equal to one and Y is equal to zero, we
have a similar situation, the angles are different,
but they have exactly

535
60:45.450 --> 60:52.380
the same relationship to
one another, and in fact, we do get exactly the
same vector that we got in the previous case.

536
60:52.380 --> 60:58.260
So the probabilities are the same and so is the winning probability.

537
60:58.260 --> 61:04.920
The last case is a little bit
different as we might expect because the winning condition
is different in this case.

538
61:04.920 --> 61:10.890
When X and Y are both equal to one, Alice and Bob win when
A and B are different.

539
61:10.890 --> 61:18.210
The basic method is the same, although the angles are different, this time, we get this vector right here

540
61:18.210 --> 61:22.260
and you can check that by going through the required subtractions.

541
61:22.260 --> 61:28.800
The probabilities do change finally, and if we look up the values that we need, we see that the probabilities
have effectively

542
61:28.800 --> 61:36.296
swapped positions from before, so this time it's the probability
that A is not equal to B, that is the larger of the two,

543
61:36.296 --> 61:42.330
but that's good because in this case, Alice and Bob win when
A and B are not equal.

544
61:42.330 --> 61:49.410
So once again, they win with
probability approximately 85%.

545
61:49.410 --> 61:56.162
Given that they win in every
case with the same probability, which is two plus root two
all over four or about 85%,

546
61:56.162 --> 62:00.600
that's the probability
that they win overall.

547
62:00.600 --> 62:07.410
That's better than any classical strategy can do for this game, and that's
what makes it interesting.

548
62:07.410 --> 62:15.690
This happens to be the
optimal winning probability for any quantum strategy, you
can't do any better than this using any entangled state.

549
62:15.690 --> 62:23.730
That fact is known Tsirelson inequality, it's named named for Boris
Tsirelson who first proved it, and to my knowledge was
one of the first people

550
62:23.730 --> 62:30.780
to describe this example as a game. In case the analysis
that we just went through seems a little bit mysterious,

551
62:30.780 --> 62:39.000
it's possible to think
about it geometrically, which might be helpful to
give you a better sense for the choice of the angles.

552
62:39.000 --> 62:45.060
Specifically, if we use the
formula that you see right here, which we can easily deduce
from the expressions

553
62:45.060 --> 62:52.770
we already found for the
inner products involved, then we can alternatively
express the probabilities of the different possible
measurement outcomes

554
62:52.770 --> 63:00.110
in the four cases as follows; first, if X, Y equals zero, zero, then these are the probabilities

555
63:00.110 --> 63:10.260
of the various measurement outcomes, and you have to either think back or look back at the analysis
that we just went through to conclude that using our formula.

556
63:10.260 --> 63:16.770
Over here, we can see the
different state vectors drawn as they were before, and the color coding here
is that blue corresponds

557
63:16.770 --> 63:22.170
to the outcome zero and red
corresponds to the outcome one.

558
63:22.170 --> 63:28.380
You can see that the angle
between the blue vectors and the angle between the red
vectors is relatively small,

559
63:28.380 --> 63:36.600
it's pi over eight in both cases, so the cosine is relatively large, and that means that the
probability that the two outcomes

560
63:36.600 --> 63:40.710
are equal is relatively large.

561
63:40.710 --> 63:48.540
In the case that X, Y equals zero, one, it's a similar situation, the
angles between the vectors having the same color is small,

562
63:48.540 --> 63:54.210
so the probability of
equal outcomes is again, relatively large.

563
63:54.210 --> 64:02.290
The third case is similar, and in the fourth case
when X, Y equals one, one, something interesting happens,
this time, just by the way,

564
64:02.290 --> 64:08.910
these vectors have been chosen, we see that the angles between
vectors having the same color

565
64:08.910 --> 64:16.350
are relatively large, and specifically the angles are three times
pi over eight in both cases.

566
64:16.350 --> 64:24.510
This means that the probability
that the measurement outcomes is equal is relatively small, but this is the one case
in which Alice and Bob win

567
64:24.510 --> 64:28.590
when their answers disagree,
so it's what we want.

568
64:28.590 --> 64:36.295
Once again, here are the vectors: when X, Y equals zero, zero,
when Xx, Y equals zero, one,

569
64:36.295 --> 64:41.970
when X, Y equals one, zero,
and when X, Y equals one, one.

570
64:41.970 --> 64:48.000
And perhaps this geometric
picture is helpful in building some intuition
for how this strategy works

571
64:48.000 --> 64:53.310
and why these various angles were chosen in the way that they were.

572
64:53.310 --> 65:00.120
To finish off the lesson, I'll make a few brief
remarks about the CHSH game.

573
65:00.120 --> 65:05.490
First, as I've already mentioned, this example isn't always
described as a game.

574
65:05.490 --> 65:13.230
In the physics community, for instance, it's more common that
the example is described simply as an experiment rather than a game

575
65:13.230 --> 65:18.930
and Alice and Bob are
viewed as being detectors rather than players.

576
65:18.930 --> 65:26.970
The basic idea of an experiment like this where entanglement leads
to statistical results that are inconsistent with
any classical description

577
65:26.970 --> 65:34.890
or more generally any
theory based on so-called local hidden variables,
is due to John Bell, the namesake of the Bell states,

578
65:34.890 --> 65:40.440
and so people often refer
to experiments of this sort as Bell tests.

579
65:40.440 --> 65:47.040
Sometimes people also
refer to Bell's theorem, which can be formulated in different ways, but it basically says
that quantum mechanics

580
65:47.040 --> 65:51.780
is not compatible with so-called local hidden variable theories.

581
65:51.780 --> 65:58.110
The CHSH game or inequality is essentially a very nice and clean
example of a Bell test,

582
65:58.110 --> 66:05.190
and you can think about
this example as a proof or a demonstration of Bell's theorem.

583
66:05.190 --> 66:12.300
The second remark is that the CHSH game offers us one way to experimentally test that the theory of quantum information

584
66:12.300 --> 66:18.630
is an accurate theory. We can actually set up experiments that implement the CHSH game,

585
66:18.630 --> 66:26.040
including the sort of
strategy based on entanglement that I had just described, and
see if it works, and it does.

586
66:26.040 --> 66:34.080
This provides us with a
high degree of confidence that entanglement is real, and unlike the perhaps
vague or poetic ways

587
66:34.080 --> 66:40.860
that we try to come up with
to explain entanglement, the CHSH game or experiment
gives us a concrete

588
66:40.860 --> 66:43.980
and testable way to observe entanglement.

589
66:43.980 --> 66:51.780
If that sounds important,
it's because it is, and the 2022 Nobel Prize
in physics acknowledges exactly this.

590
66:51.780 --> 66:58.440
The prize was awarded to
Alain Aspect, John Clauser, who is the C in CHSH, and Anton Zeilinger

591
66:58.440 --> 67:07.747
for experiments with entangled photons that established the violation
of Bell inequalities, or in other words, that
showed that quantum strategies

592
67:07.747 --> 67:12.090
of the sort that I described actually work and outperform classical strategies.

593
67:12.090 --> 67:18.330
And if you're interested in
learning more about this, I encourage you to check out
the video on Bells Theorem by my colleague Olivia Lanes,

594
67:18.330 --> 67:22.529
right here on the Qiskit YouTube channel.

595
67:22.529 --> 67:29.730
And finally, the topic of
non-local games more generally is truly fascinating, and it's
an active area of research

596
67:29.730 --> 67:36.090
that brings together
physics, computer science, and pure mathematics and there are still many
interesting questions

597
67:36.090 --> 67:40.830
about non-local games that
remain unanswered to this day.

598
67:40.830 --> 67:47.670
And that is the end of lesson four, as well as the end of
unit one of the series on the Basics of Quantum Information.

599
67:47.670 --> 67:54.240
The first lesson explained
how quantum information works for single systems in isolation, and the second lesson explained
how quantum information

600
67:54.240 --> 68:00.774
works for multiple systems,
which pretty naturally emerges from how it works for single systems.

601
68:00.774 --> 68:07.500
The third lesson introduced
the quantum circuit model of computation, and in the fourth lesson, we took a look at three important examples

602
68:07.500 --> 68:11.340
that illustrate things we
can do with entanglement.

603
68:11.340 --> 68:17.910
Along the way, we saw some very important mathematical concepts,
including tensor products and inner products, and we observed

604
68:17.910 --> 68:22.290
some fundamental limitations
of quantum information.

605
68:22.290 --> 68:28.410
I hope you'll join me for
the next unit of the series, which will be on quantum algorithms, where we'll focus on the question

606
68:28.410 --> 68:32.880
of what computational advantages
quantum information offers.

607
68:32.880 --> 68:33.873
Goodbye until then.
